This Work

ce:section.ce:para:
Food safety is a core issue associated with human safety, the social economy, and consumer perception and demand (
                     Zhao et al., 2018
                     ). Tetracycline (Tc), a priority antibiotic, has been widely utilized as a feed additive in aquaculture and animal husbandry because of its broad-spectrum antibacterial activity, good oral absorption, and low cost (
                     Li, Zhang, et al., 2020a
                     ; 
                     Hou et al., 2016
                     ; 
                     Hu et al., 2020
                     ). However, owing to the incomplete metabolism of Tc, its overuse can lead to drug residues in edible animal products (e.g., milk, meat, eggs, fish, and honey), which can cause irreversible damage to human health, including hepatotoxicity, allergic reactions, and bacterial resistance to antibiotics (
                     Han et al., 2020
                     ; 
                     Wang et al., 2018
                     ). Cu is also used as a feed additive for growth promotion in animal farming. The addition of both Tc and Cu to animal feed has led to the coexistence of these two pollutants in animal excretions, thus, resulting in pollution from complexes of Cu2+ and Tc and increasing the threat to public health and the surrounding environment (
                     Mahajan et al., 2019
                     ; 
                     Falcone et al., 2021
                     ; 
                     Armin et al., 2024
                     ). Therefore, a rapid and sensitive method for the simultaneous detection of Tc and Cu2+ is urgently needed.

Traditional instrument testing techniques, such as AAS (
                     Ozdemir, 2019
                     ), HPLC (
                     Gil et al., 2022
                     ), and ICP-MS (
                     Fanna et al., 2020
                     ), require expensive instrumentation and complex sample preprocessing, limiting their application to rapid on-site analysis. Fluorescence analysis has received increasing attention because of its numerous advantages over the aforementioned methods (
                     Sh. Mohammed Ameen et al., 2022
                     ). At the same time, with the development of technology routinisation, easy and fast smartphone-assisted visual inspection modes are also more widely used in fluorescence ratio inspection (Mohammed Ameen et al., 2023
                     ). In particular, ratiometric fluorescent probes (
                     Yu et al., 2023
                     ; 
                     Dong et al., 2012
                     ) can increase selectivity and avoid the influence of external factors via the self-calibration process of multicolor changes, thus achieving rapid visual monitoring. However, developing and establishing a ratiometric fluorescent sensor for Tc is challenging because its wide absorption band in the range between 220 and 430 nm quenches probe fluorescence via IFE (
                     Zhang et al., 2021
                     ; 
                     Patyra & Kwiatek, 2021
                     ). Numerous luminescent molecules are used for various analyses, and among them, lanthanide (III) complexes have gained increasing attention owing to their large Stokes shifts, narrow emission bands, long lifetimes, and chemical stabilities (
                     Yin & Tong, 2021; Yin & Tong, 2022
                     ). and Eu3+-Tc coordination can be utilized to detect trace amounts of Tc. Unfortunately, their inherent drawbacks, which include poor photostability and solubility, limit their practical applications. Compared with Eu-doped fluorescent nanoparticles, lanthanide coordination polymers (LCPs) have advantages such as low cost and the feasibility of mass production. Recently, non-toxic biopolymers, such as chitosan, have been explored for use in eco-friendly lanthanide complexes to detect luminescence. Moreover, poly(aspartic) acid (PAsp), a linear polypeptide constructed from repeating units of aspartic acid, is widely used in biological applications because of its water solubility, biodegradability, and ease of functionalization (
                     Hossein et al., 2021
                     ; 
                     Obot et al., 2022
                     ). PAsp is also used as a metal chelator in combination with radionuclides for targeted tumor therapy (
                     Lu et al., 2012
                     ). However, further functionalization of PAsp for sensor applications has rarely been reported. The preparation of water-soluble Eu3+-PAsp complexes using physical or chemical methods can further extend the application of luminescent lanthanides in the field of fluorescence sensing.

EDTA-functionalized PASP biopolymers prepared according to previously published methods (
                        Lu et al., 2012
                        ) and further improved upon. Firstly, 0.1 g of PASP was dissolved in 10 mM bicarbonate buffer by a magnetic stirrer, followed by 12 h incubation of 0.6 g of DMTMM and 0.87 g of DET to get PASP-DET. Next, 1.35 g of EDTA disodium salt and 0.11 g of DMTMM were dissolved in bicarbonate buffer (pH 8.5) and stirred for 10 min to activate the carboxyl group. After incubation with 0.18 g of PASP-DET for 12 h, the mixture was purified by membrane dialysis (MW 1000 Da) in bicarbonate buffer and deionized water, and then was stored at 4 °C (PASP-EDTA).

In order to assess the applicability of the PASP-FL-Eu nanoprobe, tap water, milk and honey samples as actual samples were purchased from a local hypermarket and pretreated according to the usual procedures and slight improvement (
                        Jia, Guo, et al., 2019
                        ; 
                        Jia, Bu, et al., 2019
                        ). Briefly, 1 % (v / v) of TCA was added to the milk samples to remove biomolecules. After sonication for 30 min, the precipitated proteins were removed. Honey samples and Tap water were firstly filtered by 0.22 μm membrane to remove small molecular suspended solids, and then diluted 50-fold and 10-fold, respectively. Subsequently, different concentrations of Tc or Cu2+(1, 5, 10 μM) standards were added to the above filtration of samples and measured by the sensor platform as the above.

The performance of PFE -Eu3+ for detecting TC s was investigated under the above optimum experimental conditions by fluorescence titrations. As shown in 
                        Fig. 4, the emission peak of fluorescein units at 519 nm remained unchanged under the excitation of 400 nm, while with the increasing concentrations of TC up to 20 μM, the characteristic fluorescence emission of Eu3+ at 592, 617, 652 enhanced significantly owing to “antenna effect”. Moreover, the introduction of the Cu2+ gradually quenched fluorescence at 617 nm due to IFE and the maximum quenching of the PFE-Tc -Cu2+ system reached 87.6 %. It can be seen that two linear fitting curves as I617/ I519 = 0.91825[TC]-0.22651 (R2 = 0.996) in the range of 0.05 –20 μM and I519/ I617 = 0.00562 [Cu2+] + 0.0674 (R2 = 0.994) in the range of 1 ∼ 100 μM. The calculated limit of detections (LODs) was calculated via 3σ/K, where σ is the standard deviation of blank measurements, K is the slope of the linear equation. The LOD of Tc is 10 nM, much lower than the allowable limit (225 nM, 676 nM) in drinking water set by the European Union and FDA (
                        Li, Zhou, et al., 2018b; 
                        Xu et al., 2019
                        ). The LOD for Cu2+ was calculated to be 333 nM, far lower than the maximum limit (20 μM) in drinking water regulated by U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA). At the same time, a clear color change from green to red and red disappears again can be observed (Fig4.a, b insets), suggesting the feasibility of visual detection of TC and Cu2+.
